INSERT INTO `news_details` VALUES (172, 150, 'en', 'uk_national_lottery_ticket_price_increase', 'UK National Lottery Ticket Price Increase', '<p align="justify">\r\n<img src="http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2013/1/16/1358364236698/National-lottery-tickets-009.jpg"  width="260" height="160" align="left" alt="UK National Lottery Ticket" />The price of a national lottery ticket is <strong>set to double on Saturday the 5th of October 2013</strong>, the first time since the UK National Lottery was introduced in 1994, sparking fury amongst raffle players who have threatened to boycott the game.<br></br>\r\nCamelot defended their decision by saying that the <strong>price increase from £1 to £2 per ticket</strong> will be offset by an increase in prize money and comprise a boost in funds received by lotto charities. The operator also claimed that the price hike meets increasing demands from consumers to win more money from the game.<p></p>\r\n<p align="justify">\r\nThus, the prize for matching three numbers will more than double to £25 pounds and the prize for matching four numbers will leap from £60 to £100. Similarly, the average Wednesday jackpot will increase from around £2.2 million to £2.5 million, and the average Saturday jackpot will increase from £4.1 million to £5 million. Finally, lotto rollover draws will see a significant increase in the number of raffle prizes on offer with each roll of the jackpot. \r\n<br></br>\r\n<img src="http://cached.imagescaler.hbpl.co.uk/resize/scaleWidth/456/?sURL=http://offlinehbpl.hbpl.co.uk/News/NST/48BB7123-F22A-7269-EA2885532C71071C.jpg"  width="250" height="150" align="right" alt="National Lottery Ticket Price to Double" />\r\nDespite Camelot''s positive claims, the <strong>jackpot for matching five numbers will drop £500 to £1,000</strong>, and the <strong>bonus ball will halve to £50,000</strong>. Camelot''s plans to double the price of the national lottery ticket have been met by protests and threats to stop playing with many venting their anger on twitter and facebook. \r\n<p align="justify">Around 800,000 players on average win a prize every week for matching three or four numbers whilst approximately 800 lottery hopefuls match five numbers or five numbers plus the bonus ball. With the foreseen increase in lottery ticket prices, the number of ticket buyers is set to decrease with many predicting the end of the National Lottery amidst a mass exodus of lottery players. Indeed, the <a href="http://euromillions.com/news-article/202/camelot-sales-increase">big increase in sales enjoyed by Camelot</a> last year may take a sharp turn. No changes on the <a href="www.euromillions.com">Euromillions</a> £2 ticket price has been announced.\r\n<p align="justify">\r\n<br></br>\r\n<a href="https://plus.google.com/109362733485861027705/posts">Anna Dobson</a>\r\n<br></br>', 'UK National Lottery Ticket Price Increase', 'price increase, national lottery, uk, 2013', 'Camelot has announced a dramatic increase in the price of a National Lottery Ticket, due this Saturday the 5th of October 2013, sparking anger amongst players.', 2, 1378283999, 4, 'Daniel Kowalsky', 'national-lottery-ticket-price-increase', NULL, '<p align="justify"><h2>National Lottery Ticket Price to Double on Saturday the 5th of October 2013</h2></p>', NULL, NULL, 1366117606, 0, 0, 0, 0, 0);
