INSERT INTO `news_details` VALUES (216, 194, 'en', 'fraudulent_lottery_claims_end_in_jail_sentences', 'Fraudulent Lottery Claims End In Jail Sentences', '<img src="http://images.click-manchester.com/admin/article/articleimages/1345465701-mpm_shopkeeper.jpg" width="200" height="200" align="left" alt="Farrakh Nizzar" />\r\n<p align="justify">\r\nWe would all like to win the <a href="www.euromillions.com">Euromillions</a> so that money no longer has to be a concern and we can look after the people we love. However, not only do lottery operators feature highly sophisticated security systems to safeguard against fraud, the consequences of making fraudulent lottery claims can be very severe, as the following people have found out. </p>\r\n<p align="justify">\r\n<strong>Shop worker Fraudulently Claims £1 Million Prize</strong>\r\n<p align="justify">\r\nBack in August 2012, a shop worker from Manchester was arrested on fraud charges after falsely claiming a £1 million Euromillions prize belonging to one of his 77 year-old customers. Winning ticket-holder Maureen Holt went to Farrakh Nizzar''s convenience store located in Oldham, Greater Manchester to see if she had won. He told her that she hadn''t and that he would throw away the ticket. However, the UK National Lottery retailer later rang a lottery hotline in his attempt to claim the £1 million cash prize stating that he had bought it from his store. His attempted fraud was only discovered when it was established that the winning ticket had been purchased using Maureen Holt''s Tesco Club Card at a Tesco Extra store, and not the Best One Convenience Store. An internal investigation followed and Farrakh Nizzar remanded in custody on charges of fraud by false representation. \r\n\r\n<p align="justify">\r\n<strong>Newsagent Couple Steals £156,000 Winning Ticket</strong>\r\n<p align="justify">\r\n<img src="http://metrouk2.files.wordpress.com/2012/03/article-1332273017727-123f4cf7000005dc-332289_362x220.jpg " width="280" height="180" align="right" alt="Alfred Jeevarajah" />\r\nSimilarly to the aforementioned shop worker, shopkeeper Anne Jeevarajah told the winner of a lucky dip ticket that she hadn''t won. Gwyn Badham-Davies took her lottery ticket to the family store in Hingham to find out if it was a lucky one. Mrs. Jeevarajah checked it on her machine but failed to mention that she had won a small fortune of £156,000. Her husband, Alfred Jeevarajah, then called lottery operator Camelot claiming that he had won. However, the delay between the date of purchase and the claim being made caused Camelot to become suspicious, especially after they discovered that Mr. Jeevarajah was a shop worker. An investigation was launched and the couple jailed for 14 months last March 2012 after admitting to theft and fraud. Mr and Mrs Badham Davies have since been paid their £156,000 cash prize. \r\n\r\n<p align="justify">\r\n<strong>Woman Falsely Claims $656 Million Mega Million Jackpot</strong>\r\n<p align="justify">\r\n<img src="http://www.triblocal.com/elgin/files/2012/05/WilliamsLeandria.jpg" width="240" height="200" align="left" alt="Leandria Williams" />\r\nA woman from Illinois claimed that she was holder of a winning ticket for the record $656 Mega Millions jackpot back in March 2012. Leandria Williams was charged for attempted theft and forgery after purchasing online lottery tickets approximately eight minutes following the Mega Millions draw on March the 30th 2013. She then attempted to manipulate the documents so it appeared that she had bought the winning ticket prior to the draw. Thanks to the Illinois Lottery''s 100% foolproof safeguards against fraud, her false claim was discovered. \r\n\r\n<p align="justify">\r\n<strong>Woman Claims She Lost $162 Million Winning Ticket</strong>\r\n<p align="justify">\r\n<img src="http://media.cleveland.com/metro/photo/elecia-battlejpg-451c549990539982_small.jpg" width="200" height="220" align="right" alt="Elecia Battle" />\r\nAll the way back in 2004, a woman from Cleveland was convicted after claiming she lost a winning lottery ticket worth $162 million. A few days following the Mega Millions drawing on December the 30th that year,  Elecia Battle filed a police report stating that she had bought the winning ticket but had lost it. Her claim was dismissed when she admitted to her lie which carried a possible penalty of 30 days to six months in jail combined with a $1,000 fine. \r\n\r\n<p align="justify">\r\n<strong>Fraudster Steals Over £570,000 in False Lottery Claims</strong>\r\n<p align="justify">\r\nAmuda Sheidu, currently serving a 27 month jail sentence, faces a further four years behind bars if he doesn''t pay back over £500,000 he gained through false lottery claims and other scams. He admitted to laundering £170,000 for an international crime gang as well as, making false lottery claims and carrying out fake charity collections, amongst others, which raked him in a staggering £578,632. \r\n<img src="http://cambs-police.co.uk/images/newsitem/download/Amuda%20Sheidu.JPG" width="240" height="220" align="left" alt="Amuda Sheidu" />\r\n£41,000 seized from his bank account was paid in compensation to three victims of the various scams, whilst he has six months to pay back the outstanding amount. The debt will still remain regardless of whether he serves the further 4 year jail sentence or not. \r\n<p align="justify">\r\nFinally, we recently mentioned that a couple almost earned themselves a jail sentence when they cashed in a winning lottery ticket they found on the supermarket floor. Find out more with <a href="http://euromillions.com/news-article/368/lottery-misses-and-near-misses">Lottery Misses and Near Misses</a> featuring winners that almost lost out on a huge cash prize!\r\n<p align="justify">\r\nTo avoid all the aforementioned occurring, players are highly advised to sign the back of their tickets as well as check if they have won before presenting them at any store. Alternatively, buying your Euromillions tickets online comprises an even more secure and convenient way to play the lottery. With regards to <a href="http://euromillions.com/scam-examples">\r\nlottery email scams</a>, find out how to recognise and avoid them <a href="http://euromillions.com/lottery-email-scams">here</a>. Make sure you never get caught out! \r\n</p>', 'Fraudulent Lottery Claims', 'fraudulent, lottery claims, false, jail, euro millions, euromillions', 'Sometimes people unsuccessfully make fraudulent lottery claims which ultimately lands them a jail sentence. Read about it here on www.euromillions.com!', 2, 1375441901, 4, 'Daniel Kowalsky', 'Fraudulent Lottery Claims', NULL, '<p align="justify"><h2>Fraudulent Lottery Claims</h2></p>', NULL, NULL, 1375433778, 0, 0, 0, 0, 0);
