INSERT INTO `news_details` VALUES (223, 201, 'en', 'campaigners_demand_425_million_big_lottery_refund', 'Campaigners Demand £425 Million Big Lottery Refund', '<img src="https://si0.twimg.com/profile_images/3120117173/5d938c6078a3193aa6b63c9117a34b3e.png" width="260" height="260" align="left" alt="Big Lottery Fund" />\r\n<p align="justify">\r\nIn 2007, the UK Government and Olympics organisers took £425 million from the Big Lottery Fund to help pay for the 2012 Summer Olympics. With charities struggling from major cuts, campaigners are demanding that the money be repaid now so that deprived communities in the UK and people who need it most can benefit. </p>\r\n<p align="justify">\r\n<strong> Big Lottery Fund</strong> \r\n<p align="justify">\r\n40% of the money raised for Good Causes by the UK National Lottery is distributed by the <a href="http://euromillions.com/news-article/337/euromillions-lottery-winners-and-good-causes">Big Lottery Fund (BIG)</a>. Thus, every 11 pence for each pound spent on a <a href="http://euromillions.com/news-article/371/new-lotto-raffle-to-replace-lotto-plus-5">Lotto ticket</a> goes to charitable projects in the UK that help communities and people who need it. A majority of the proceeds, corresponding to a total of around £600 million per year, are allocated to voluntary and community sector organisations supporting health, the environment and education, amongst others. BIG also awards funding on behalf of UK public bodies including the Office for Civil Society and the Department for Education. </p>\r\n<p align="justify">\r\n<strong>Big Lottery Refund</strong> \r\n<p align="justify">\r\nIn 2007, £425 million in funds which should have been distributed to charitable projects across the UK by BIG, were raided by the UK Government and Olympic organisers. After London won the bid for the 2012 Summer Olympics, they realised that Olympics budget needed to be trebled to a staggering £9.3 billion, including a multi-billion pound contingency. Thus, a further £675 million in lottery revenues was raided by the UK Government, £425 million of which belonged to BIG. \r\nIn fact, BIG inadvertently became the largest contributor to the games as the UK Government had already planned to take £213 million to support the original budget.</p>\r\n</p><img src="http://www.biglotteryrefund.org.uk/images/BigLotteryRefund.jpg" width="260" height="180" align="right" alt="Big Lottery Refund" />\r\n<p align="justify">\r\nThe £213 million, plus the £425 million taken by the UK Government, took BIG''s total contribution to a whopping £638 million. At the time, their decision was highly criticised thus, in response the government agreed a Memorandum of Understanding (MOU) with the Mayor of London related to reimbursing the money using the proceeds from selling Olympic assets. Although no particular date or time frame was established in the MOU, the repayment was expected to be prompt. The current government said it would honour the agreement however, following several revisions of the original agreement, they announced that repayment of the £675 million would take place over a period of 25 years “with the full £675 million potentially paid by 2030/2031”.</p> \r\n<p align="justify">\r\nThe <a href="http://www.biglotteryrefund.org.uk/">Big Lottery Refund</a> comprises a campaign from the Directory of Social Change (DSC) who are fighting to get this money paid back as soon as possible so that communities across the UK can benefit from the funds now, and not in several decades time. They accused the UK Government of using charities as an insurance policy for the Games planners whilst according to the DSC, the £425 million they took could have funded at least 10,000 charities and helped more than 8 million people.</p>\r\n<p align="justify">\r\n<img src="http://db2.stb.s-msn.com/i/EF/C1D483A85B333B8B84A355AC38A65.jpg" width="250" height="305" align="left" alt="Lottery Funded" />\r\n<p align="justify">\r\nDespite the UK Government''s promises, they fear that this assets deal is neither “credible or reliable” with the given length of time involved subjecting the contract to amendments, or even the threat of being broken. </p>\r\n<p align="justify">\r\n<strong>100 Millionaires Raffle 2012</strong>\r\n<p align="justify">\r\nAs a means of saying thank you to UK Lotto players for helping raise the necessary funds, lottery operator Camelot held a special 100 Millionaires Raffle on the 27th of July 2012, coinciding with the 2012 Olympics Opening Ceremony. It set records for the highest number of newly-made millionaires in a single draw and, alongside the <a href="http://euromillions.com/news-article/363/100-uk-millionaires-guaranteed-in-100-millionaires-raffle-this-july">100 Millionaires Raffle</a> held on Friday the 26th of July 2013, boasts the largest lottery draw ever.  </p>\r\n<p align="justify">\r\nDespite this, the DSC claims that the money was intended to benefit charitable causes and that it shouldn''t have been taken in the first place. \r\n</p>\r\n<br></br>\r\n<iframe width="580" height="320" src="http://www.youtube.com/embed/SseSg4Qw42E?feature=player_embedded" frameborder="0" allowfullscreen></iframe>\r\n<p align="justify">\r\n<br></br>\r\n<a href="https://plus.google.com/109362733485861027705/posts">Anna Dobson</a>\r\n<br></br>', 'Big Lottery Refund Campaign', 'big lottery refund, campaign, directory of social change, lottery, euro millions, ', '£425 million were taken from the Big Lottery Fund to pay for the 2012 Summer Olympics. Campaigners are now claiming the money back from the UK Goverment.', 2, 1377171038, 4, 'Daniel Kowalsky', 'big-lottery-refund', NULL, '<p align="justify"><h2>UK Government Raided BIG to Help Fund 2012 Summer Olympics</h2></p>', NULL, NULL, 1377168543, 0, 0, 0, 0, 0);
